{{Use mdy dates|date=October 2015}} {{Infobox musical artist <!--See Wikipedia:WikiProject Musicians --> | name = 88-Keys | background = solo_singer | birth_name = Charles Misodi Njapa | birth_date = {{Birth date and age|1976|3|5}} | birth_place = [[New York City]], [[New York (state)|New York]], [[United States|US]] | genre = [[Hip hop music|Hip hop]] | occupation = [[Record producer]], [[rapping|rapper]] | years_active = 1998–present | label = [[GOOD Music]], [[Decon Records|Decon]], Locksmith Music | associated_acts = [[Kanye West]], [[Peter Bjorn and John]], [[Kid Cudi]], [[Consequence (rapper)|Consequence]], [[The Pharcyde]], [[Black Star (group)|Black Star]] | website = {{URL|www.myspace.com/88keys}} }}
'''Charles Misodi Njapa''' (born March 5, 1976), better known by his [[stage name]] '''88-Keys''', is an [[United States|American]] [[record producer]] and [[rapping|rapper]] from [[New York City]].
==Biography== Born in [[New York City]] to West African parents, he was raised in the [[Eastchester, Bronx|Eastchester]] section of the [[Bronx]] and later in [[West Hempstead, New York|West Hempstead]] on [[Long Island]], where he attended high school.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.latimes.com/style/la-ig-styleprofile23-2008nov23-story.html |title=Polo Ralph Lauren fits 88-Keys just fine |work=[[Los Angeles Times]] |date=November 23, 2008}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=http://firstwefeast.com/eat/cooking-at-home-with-88-keys |title=Cooking at Home with 88-Keys |work=First We Feast |date=July 8, 2013}}</ref>
88-Keys first took an interest in [[Hip hop music|hip hop]] after hearing [[Prince Paul (producer)|Prince Paul]]'s [[Hip hop production|production]] on [[De La Soul]]'s 1989 critically acclaimed album ''[[3 Feet High and Rising]]''.<ref name="Decon Records">{{cite web |url=http://www.deconrecords.com/artists/88-keys/88-keys-bio/ |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180911003024/http://www.deconrecords.com/artists/88-keys/88-keys-bio/ |dead-url=yes |archive-date=2018-09-11 |title=88-Keys Bio |publisher=Decon Records |date= |accessdate=2008-08-29}} </ref> In the early '90's, 88-Keys met [[A Tribe Called Quest]]'s [[Q-Tip (rapper)|Q-Tip]], DJ-producer [[Pete Rock]] and producer [[Large Professor]] working as an intern at West Hempstead's The Music Palace recording studio. It was Large Professor who gave Charles his 88-Keys moniker after witnessing his skills on the [[Ensoniq ASR-10]] keyboard.<ref name="Dork Magazine">{{cite web |url=http://www.dorkmag.com/dm_issue3_88keys_page1.html |title=88-keys: The Process of Making a Beat |publisher=Dork Magazine |date= |accessdate=2008-09-03 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080919221143/http://www.dorkmag.com/dm_issue3_88keys_page1.html |archivedate=September 19, 2008 |deadurl=no}}</ref>
However, 88-Keys's parents were strict on education and less enthusiastic about his interest in the then-newly emerging cultural phenomenon of hip hop. Both of 88-Keys's parents are registered nurses, his brother is a doctor, one of his older sisters is a nurse and another sister is on her way to becoming a doctor. Upon considering a serious career in music, 88-Keys's parents and older brother began trying to point him into the field of medicine because it was a more "professional field" and the music industry didn't seem like a lucrative move.<ref name="sixshot.com">{{cite web|url=http://www.sixshot.com/interviews/11731/ |title=88-Keys – The Piano Man |publisher=Serge Fleury |date=2008-07-09 |accessdate=2008-09-07 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080802044814/http://www.sixshot.com/interviews/11731/ |archivedate=August 2, 2008 |deadurl=no |df=mdy }}</ref> After briefly attending [[Hofstra University]] and [[Queens College]], 88-Keys dropped out to pursue his dreams of being a record producer. His decision was fueled by an opportunity to record some tracks with [[The Pharcyde]] who were recording in [[California]].<ref name="remixmag.com">{{cite web |url=http://remixmag.com/artists/hiphop_R&B/remix_solid_rock/ |title=Solid as a Rock |publisher=Anthony Roberts |date=2008-05-01 |accessdate=2008-09-07 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080718145226/http://remixmag.com/artists/hiphop_R%26B/remix_solid_rock |archive-date=July 18, 2008 |dead-url=yes |df=mdy-all }}</ref> 88-Keys currently resides in [[Harlem]], New York with his wife and two daughters.
In addition to his passion for music, 88-Keys has expressed his love for fashion, most notably [[Ralph Lauren]]. During an interview with ''[[Metro International|Metro]]'' 88-Keys revealed that he has worn [[Polo Ralph Lauren]] every day for 16 years. {{cquote|''I try to stay true to Ralph's vision. I don't want to bastardize his vision — no offense to the urban community — because we all know what happened to Tommy Hilfiger once the hip hop community embraced it. I'll walk out of the door dressed in loafers when everyone else is wearing Timberland boots. I definitely stand out. I'll tag along with Kanye on shopping trips and look at clothing by designers whose names I'd need to take French lessons to pronounce. He'll ask me what I think and I'll be like, whatever. I've turned down paying gigs because they've tried to dress me in clothing by other designers. Besides record shopping, the only other place I need is a Polo store. I'll go to [[Paris]] and they ll be like, 'here's the Eiffel Tower' and I'm like, 'whatever, where's the record store and the Polo store.''<ref name="Metronews">{{cite web |url=http://www.metronews.ca/calgary/comment/article/138817 |title=Sticking with the Brand |publisher=Kenya Hunt |date=2008-11-10 |accessdate=2008-11-17 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090328120602/http://www.metronews.ca/calgary/comment/article/138817 |archive-date=March 28, 2009 |dead-url=yes |df=mdy-all }}</ref>}} According to the article, 88-Keys began wearing Polo Ralph Lauren as a Long Island high school student in 1992 when he developed a liking for its classic, preppy style. Since then, he's worn a complete look from the brand every day, without fail. His wardrobe includes over 700 Polo pieces.<ref name="Metronews" />
Since his days as an assistant engineer, 88-Keys has produced records for numerous artists including [[Mos Def]], [[Talib Kweli]], [[Kid Cudi]], [[Macy Gray]], [[Musiq Soulchild]], [[Dejuan Lucian]] and [[Consequence (rapper)|Consequence]]. Recently, 88-Keys extended beyond his production credits to highlight his skills on the mic as [[MC]], [[singer]] and [[Collaboration|collaborator]], most notably on his solo debut album ''[[The Death of Adam]]'' released on November 11, 2008. [[Executive producer#Music|Executively produced]] by 88-Keys's close friend [[Kanye West]],<ref name="kanyeuniversecity">{{cite web |url=http://www.kanyeuniversecity.com/blog/?em3106=204202_-1__0_~0_-1_8_2008_0_0&em3281=&em3161 |title=88-Keys "The Death of Adam" News Piece #2 |accessdate=2008-09-03 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080916183851/http://www.kanyeuniversecity.com/blog/?em3106=204202_-1__0_~0_-1_8_2008_0_0&em3281=&em3161 |archivedate=September 16, 2008 |deadurl=yes |df=mdy-all }}</ref> the [[concept album]] tells the story of a man named Adam who has been murdered in a loft apartment in Harlem.<ref name="DJBooth.net">{{cite web |url=http://www.djbooth.net/index/tracks/review/88-keys-ft-kanye-west-stay-up-viagra/ |title=88-Keys ft. Kanye West – Stay Up (Viagra) |publisher=M. Burmy |date=2008-08-26 |accessdate=2008-08-29 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080829221650/http://www.djbooth.net/index/tracks/review/88-keys-ft-kanye-west-stay-up-viagra/ |archivedate=August 29, 2008 |deadurl=no}}</ref> In August 2008 a fifteen-track [[mixtape]] titled ''Adam's Case Files'' was released as a prequel to ''The Death of Adam''. The album's first single titled "[[Stay Up! (Viagra)]]" was officially released through iTunes on September 9, 2008. In December 2008, 88-Keys was highlighted as ''[[Spin (magazine)]]'' Artist of the Day.<ref name="Spin.com">{{cite web |url=http://spin.com/articles/88-keys |title=ARTIST OF THE DAY: 88-KEYS |publisher=Joseph Coscarelli |date=2008-12-11 |accessdate=2008-12-29 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20081217120654/http://www.spin.com/articles/88-keys |archivedate=December 17, 2008 |deadurl=no}}</ref> In 2009, 88-Keys worked in [[Atlanta]] with new female duo [[Addictive (British band)|Addictive]] on a track for a forthcoming album.
==Discography== {{main|88-Keys production discography}} * ''Adam's Case Files Mixtape'' (2008) * ''Stay Up! (Viagra) Prescription Pack – EP'' (2008) * ''[[The Death of Adam]]'' (2008)
