{{Infobox military person | name = Abu'l-Qasim Ali ibn al-Hasan al-Kalbi | image = | image_size = | alt = | caption = | birth_date = | birth_place = | death_date = 13 July 982 | death_place = [[Capo Colonna]] | placeofburial_label = | placeofburial = | placeofburial_coordinates = | allegiance = [[Emirate of Sicily]] ([[Fatimid Caliphate]]) | serviceyears = 23 June 970 – 13 July 982 | commands = [[Emir of Sicily]] | battles_label = | battles = | spouse = | relations = [[al-Hasan ibn Ali al-Kalbi]] (father), [[Ahmad ibn al-Hasan al-Kalbi]] (brother) | dynasty = [[Kalbids|Kalbid Dynasty]] | laterwork = }}
'''Abu'l-Qasim Ali ibn al-Hasan al-Kalbi''' ({{lang-ar|أبو القاسم علي بن الحسن الكلبي}}; ''Abū'l-Qāsim ʿAlī ibn al-Ḥasan al-Kalbī''), known to the [[Byzantine Empire|Byzantine]] [[Greek people|Greeks]] as '''Bolkasimos''', was the fourth [[Emirate of Sicily|Emir of Sicily]]. He ruled from June 23, 970 to his death in battle on July 13, 982.
== Background == In 947, the [[Fatimid]] [[caliph]] [[al-Mansur Billah]] sent [[al-Hasan ibn Ali al-Kalbi]] to subdue a revolt on [[Sicily]], where he would go on to establish his own ruling dynasty, the [[Kalbids]]. Al-Hasan was succeeded by his son, [[Ahmad ibn al-Hasan al-Kalbi]], in 954. In 969 Ahmad was recalled to [[North Africa]] to assist in subduing a revolt by Berber tribesmen.{{sfn|PmbZ|loc=Ya'īš (#28457)}} Briefly in 969, one of Ahmad's freed slaves, Ya'ish, was appointed governor of Sicily.{{sfn|PmbZ|loc=Ya'īš (#28457)}} The next year Abu'l-Qasim, Ahmad's brother, was elevated to governor.{{sfn|PmbZ|loc=Abū-Qāsim'Alī b. al-Ḥasan al-Kalbī (#20072)}}
== Rule == During the spring of 976, Abu'l-Qasim launched a raiding expedition on [[Byzantine Italy]].{{sfn|Kaldellis|2017|p=82}} His first target was the city of [[Messina]], which he found deserted upon arrival.{{sfn|PmbZ|loc=Abū-Qāsim'Alī b. al-Ḥasan al-Kalbī (#20072)}} He soon moved on to [[Apulia]], taking tribute from [[Cosenza]] before sending his brother to raid the surrounding countryside. He soon crossed the straits back to Sicily.{{sfn|PmbZ|loc=Abū-Qāsim'Alī b. al-Ḥasan al-Kalbī (#20072)}}{{sfn|Kaldellis|2017|p=82}} During the summer of the same year, Abu'l-Qasim crossed back to mainland Italy, where he quickly forced tribute out of St. Agatha and took and razed [[Taranto]]. He then sent one army to [[Otranto]] while he besieged [[Gravina in Puglia|Gravina]], before retiring to Muslim lands for the year, bringing home hundreds of captives as slaves.{{sfn|Kaldellis|2017|p=82}}
In May 982, Abu'l-Qasim returned to Italy hoping to confront the advancing German emperor [[Otto II, Holy Roman Emperor|Otto II]].{{sfn|PmbZ|loc=Abū-Qāsim'Alī b. al-Ḥasan al-Kalbī (#20072)}} Around [[Rossano Calabro]], Abu'l-Qasim spotted the German army and realized that he had hugely underestimated its size. He attempted to retreat back to Sicily, but Otto caught up with him around [[Capo Colonna]]. In the [[Battle of Stilo]], the outnumbered Kalbid force was able to surround and defeat the German forces with an unexpectedly strong cavalry charge;{{sfn|Barkowski|2015|pp=170–173}} Otto himself only escaped by swimming to a Greek merchant ship,<ref>''The Place of Byzantium in the Medieval World'', Steve Runciman, ''The Cambridge Medieval History'', Vol. IV., Part II, ed. J.M. Hussey, (Cambridge University Press, 1967), 361.</ref> but Abu'l-Qasim was killed in the melee.{{sfn|PmbZ|loc=Abū-Qāsim'Alī b. al-Ḥasan al-Kalbī (#20072)}}
