{{Redirect|Bernardo I|other people|Bernardo I of Kongo}}

'''Bernardo I of Kongo''' (died 1567) was a 16th-century [[manikongo]] (ruler) of the [[Kingdom of Kongo]], a region encompassing areas in 21st-century [[Angola]] and the [[Democratic Republic of Congo]]. He came to power after murdering his half-brother [[Afonso II of Kongo|Afonso II]] who was less well-disposed toward the Portuguese.

The rule of Bernardo I extended from 1561 to 1567.<ref>[[John Thornton (historian)|Thornton, John]] (2006): "Elite Women in the Kingdom of Kongo: Historical Perspectives on Women's Political Power", page 447. ''The Journal of African History'', Vol. 47.</ref> He was killed fighting the [[Yaka people|Yaka]] on Kongo's eastern frontier.<ref>[[Roland Oliver|Oliver, Roland]] and Atmore, Anthony (2001): ''Medieval Africa, 1250-1800'', page 173. Cambridge University Press.</ref> The Yaka, who were referred to as [[Jagas]] by the [[Kingdom of Kongo|Essikongo]] and the [[Portuguese Empire|Portuguese]], would invade and nearly conquer Kongo in 1568.

