*[[Suicide of Jamie Hubley|Jamie Hubley]] (1995–2011), age 15, died by suicide in October 14, 2011. The Ottawa teen was subjected to anti-gay bullying. Hubley's death was the impetus for the Accepting Schools Act, 2012, an act of the [[Legislative Assembly of Ontario]] which mandated school boards across the province to develop tougher anti-bullying programs with tougher penalties for infractions, and offered legal protections for [[gay-straight alliance]]s in the province's schools.<ref>[https://www.theglobeandmail.com/news/politics/anti-bullying-bill-passes-clearing-way-for-gay-straight-alliances-in-ontario-schools/article4231542/ "Anti-bullying bill passes, clearing way for gay-straight alliances in Ontario schools"]. ''[[The Globe and Mail]]'', June 5, 2012.</ref> On June 3, 2013, Allan Hubley (the father of Jamie) and [[Laureen Harper]] announced a new federal anti-bullying strategy, which will see approximately 2,400 teenagers across Canada trained in delivering [[peer education]] workshops and presentations against bullying for their fellow students.<ref>[http://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/ottawa/story/2013/06/02/feds-ottawa-bullying-hubley.html "Feds pledge $250K to youth-led anti-bullying project"]. [[CBC News]], June 3, 2013.</ref>
* [[Suicide of Jamey Rodemeyer|Jamey Rodemeyer]] (1997–2011), age 14, was a gay<ref>http://hausofjamey-blog.tumblr.com</ref> teenager, known for his [[activism]] against [[homophobia]] and his videos on [[YouTube]] to help victims of homophobic bullying. He ended his life by hanging himself, allegedly as a result of constant bullying.<ref name="NYT20110921">{{cite news |author=Anahad O'Connor |authorlink=Anahad O'Connor |title=Suicide Draws Attention to Gay Bullying |newspaper=[[The New York Times]] |date=September 21, 2011 |url=http://well.blogs.nytimes.com/2011/09/21/suicide-of-gay-teenager-who-urged-hope/ |accessdate=October 17, 2011}}</ref>
* [[Suicide of Audrie Pott|Audrie Pott]] (1997–2012), age 15, a student attending [[Saratoga High School (California)|Saratoga High School]], [[California]]. She died of suicide by hanging on September 12, 2012.  She had been allegedly sexually assaulted by three teenage boys at a party eight days earlier and pictures of the assault were posted online with accompanying bullying.{{citation needed|date=October 2017}} Pott's suicide and the circumstances surrounding it have been compared to the [[suicide of Rehtaeh Parsons]], a young woman in Canada, appearing to show highly similar characteristics. New laws are being considered as a result of these events.<ref name="CBC-Pott">{{cite news|url=http://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/nova-scotia/story/2013/04/12/ns-rehteah-audrey-alleged-bullying-sex-assault.html|title=U.S. teen's death eerily similar to Rehtaeh Parsons's story - Nova Scotia - CBC News|date=12 April 2013|work=[[CBC News]]|accessdate=12 April 2013}}</ref><ref name="CBC-Pott-2">{{cite news|url=http://www.cbc.ca/news/world/story/2013/04/12/us-teens-arrested-girl-suicide.html|title=3 U.S. teens arrested for sexual battery after girl's suicide - World - CBC News|date=12 April 2013|work=[[CBC News]]|accessdate=13 April 2013}}</ref>
* [[Suicide of Amanda Todd|Amanda Todd]] (1996–2012), age 15, Canadian high school student who died of suicide by hanging due to school bullying and cyberbullying.<ref>Grenoble, Ryan (October 10, 2012). [http://www.huffingtonpost.com/mobileweb/2012/10/11/amanda-todd-suicide-bullying_n_1959909.html "Amanda Todd: Bullied Canadian Teen Commits Suicide After Prolonged Battle Online And In School "]. ''[[The Huffington Post]]''.</ref> She died by suicide at the age of 15 at her home in [[Port Coquitlam]], British Columbia, Canada. Prior to her death, Todd had posted a video on YouTube in which she used a series of flash cards to tell her experience of allegedly being blackmailed into exposing her breasts via webcam;<ref name="Suspect">[http://news.msn.com/crime-justice/dutch-mans-case-linked-to-amanda-todd Dutch man's case linked to Amanda Todd], ''MSN.com'', 18 April 2014, Hainsworth, J., Retrieved 18 April 2014.</ref> bullied; and physically assaulted. The video went [[Viral video|viral]] after her death,<ref name="cbccareport">{{cite news|url= http://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/calgary/story/2012/11/18/bc-amanda-todd-celebration-of-life.html |title=Amanda Todd tribute honors life of bullied teen | place = Calgary, CA | publisher = [[CBC.ca|CBC]] | work = News|date=November 18, 2012 |accessdate=November 24, 2012 | quote=After she died, the video gained worldwide recognition and registered more than six million hits, and copies of the video re-posted to YouTube have since gained at least 16 million additional hits.}}</ref> resulting in international media attention. The video has had more than 19 million views as of May 2015.<ref name="Suspect" />  The [[Royal Canadian Mounted Police]] and British Columbia Coroners Service launched investigations into the suicide. At the time of her death, Todd was a [[Tenth grade|grade 10]] student<ref name="washingtonpost1">{{cite news|author=Associated Press |url= http://www.foxnews.com/world/2012/10/12/canadian-teen-found-dead-weeks-after-posting-wrenching-youtube-video-detailing/ |title= Canadian teen found dead weeks after posting wrenching YouTube video detailing bullying |publisher=Fox News |date = 2012-10-12 |accessdate=October 31, 2012}}</ref> at CABE Secondary in Coquitlam,<ref>{{cite web |last=Luymes |first=Glenda |url=http://www.theprovince.com/news/Cyberbullying+Amanda+Todd+suicide+prompts+grief/7376942/story.html |title=Cyberbullying: Outpouring of grief over teen's suicide (with video) |publisher=The province |date=March 25, 2002 |accessdate=October 13, 2012 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20121014091826/http://www.theprovince.com/news/Cyberbullying+Amanda+Todd+suicide+prompts+grief/7376942/story.html |archivedate=October 14, 2012 |df= }}</ref> a school that caters to students who have experienced social and behavior issues in previous educational settings.<ref>{{cite web| title = About CABE | url = http://www.sd43.bc.ca/secondary/CABE/About/Pages/ | publisher= sd43 |accessdate= November 5, 2012 | location = BC, CA}}</ref> In response to the death, [[Christy Clark]], the [[premier of British Columbia]], made an online statement of condolence and suggested a national discussion on criminalizing [[cyberbullying]].<ref>{{cite news | title = RCMP launch investigation into death of bullied BC teen| place = CA | url= http://www.ctvnews.ca/canada/rcmp-launch-investigation-into-death-of-bullied-b-c-teen-1.993029 |accessdate=October 13, 2012|newspaper=CTV News}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=After Amanda Todd's death, Christy Clark says new laws may be needed to combat bullying | url = http://www.vancouversun.com/life/After+Amanda+Todd+death+Christy+Clark+says+laws+needed+combat/7384108/story.html |publisher=Vancouver Sun|accessdate=October 13, 2012}}</ref> Also, a motion was introduced in the Canadian House of Commons to propose a study of the scope of bullying in Canada, and for more funding and support for anti-bullying organizations. Todd's mother Carol established the Amanda Todd Trust, receiving donations to support anti-bullying awareness education and programs for young people with mental health problems.
* [[Suicide of Kenneth Weishuhn|Kenneth Weishuhn]] (1997–2012), age 14, was a teen who is known for his suicide which raised the national profile on gay bullying and LGBT youth suicides. Weishuhn, then 14 years old, was allegedly bullied in person, death threats were sent to his mobile phone, and he was the subject of a [[Facebook]] hate group. He was targeted for being gay, having come out one month before his suicide. Weishuhn told his mother Jeannie Chambers "Mom, you don't know how it feels to be hated". The bullying was characterized as "aggressive",<ref name=Horlyk1>{{cite web|last=Horlyk|first=Earl|title=Sister: Bullying led Primghar teen to suicide|url=http://siouxcityjournal.com/news/local/state-and-regional/sister-bullying-led-primghar-teen-to-suicide/article_9fa262c6-a8be-5187-ad4c-8fb31ffa683c.html|publisher=Sioux City Journal|accessdate=21 March 2014}}</ref> "merciless"<ref name=Swartley1>{{cite web|last=Swartley|first=Kristen|title=Anti-Bullying Vigil Held in Cedar Falls In Response to Gay Iowa Teen's Suicide|url=http://cedarfalls.patch.com/groups/breast-cancer-awareness/p/cedar-falls-vigil-for-kenneth-j-weishuhn-jr|accessdate=21 March 2014}}</ref>  and "overwhelming".<ref name=Hector1>{{cite web|last=Hector|first=Marypat|title=Bullied To DEATH!|url=http://globalgrind.com/2012/04/19/kenneth-weishuhn-jr-bullied-gay-teen-commits-suicide-bullied-death/|publisher=Global Grind|accessdate=21 March 2014}}</ref>  In response to the bullying, Weishuhn took his own life in April 2012.<ref name=Huff1>{{cite news|title=Kenneth Weishuhn, Gay Iowa Teen, Commits Suicide After Allegedly Receiving Death Threats|url=http://www.huffingtonpost.com/2012/04/17/kenneth-weishuhn-gay-iowa-teen-suicide_n_1431442.html|accessdate=21 March 2014|newspaper=Huffington Post|date=17 April 2012}}</ref> He [[Suicide by hanging|hanged]] himself in the family's garage.<ref name=Munson1>{{cite news|title=Munson: Year after bullied teen's death, family has seen his story spread |url=http://www.desmoinesregister.com/article/20130414/NEWS03/304140047/Munson-Year-after-bullied-teen-s-death-family-has-seen-his-story-spread |archive-url=https://archive.is/20140322022139/http://www.desmoinesregister.com/article/20130414/NEWS03/304140047/Munson-Year-after-bullied-teen-s-death-family-has-seen-his-story-spread |dead-url=yes |archive-date=22 March 2014 |accessdate=21 March 2014 |newspaper=Desmoines Register }}</ref><ref name=MunsonKenenth1>{{cite web|last=Munson |first=Kyle |title=Munson: Year after bullied teen's death, family has seen his story spread |url=http://www.desmoinesregister.com/article/20130414/NEWS03/304140047/Munson-Year-after-bullied-teen-s-death-family-has-seen-his-story-spread?nclick_check=1 |archive-url=https://archive.is/20140322022203/http://www.desmoinesregister.com/article/20130414/NEWS03/304140047/Munson-Year-after-bullied-teen-s-death-family-has-seen-his-story-spread?nclick_check=1 |dead-url=yes |archive-date=22 March 2014 |publisher=Des Moines Register |accessdate=21 March 2014 }}</ref>
* [[Suicide of Jadin Bell|Jadin Bell]] (1997–2013), age 15, was an [[Oregon]] youth known for his suicide which raised the national profile on youth bullying and [[gay bashing|gay victimization in bullying]]. Bell, a 15-year-old gay youth, was allegedly intensely bullied both in person and on the [[Cyberbullying|internet]] because he was gay. He was a member of the [[La Grande High School]] [[Cheerleading#High school|cheer leading team]] in [[La Grande, Oregon]], where he was a sophomore. On January 14, 2013, Bell went to a local elementary school and hanged himself from the play structure. He did not immediately die from the strangulation and was rushed to the emergency room, where he was kept on life support.<ref>{{cite news|title=Jadin Bell, Gay Oregon Teen, Taken Off Life Support After Hanging Himself|url=http://www.huffingtonpost.com/2013/01/29/jadin-bell-gay-oregon-teen-hanging-suicide-life-support-_n_2576404.html|accessdate=15 March 2014|newspaper=The Huffington Post|date=29 January 2014}}</ref> The [[Associated Press]] reported that a spokesman for the [[Oregon Health and Science University]]'s [[Portland, Oregon|Portland]] hospital announced that after being taken off [[life support]] Bell died on February 3, 2013.<ref name=Huff2>{{cite news|last=Associated Press|title=Jadin Bell Dead: Gay Oregon Teen Who Hanged Himself Dies After Being Taken Off Life Support|url=http://www.huffingtonpost.com/2013/02/04/jadin-bell-dead-gay-oregon-teen-hanging_n_2617909.html|accessdate=15 March 2014|newspaper=Huffington Post|date=4 February 2013}}</ref> Bell's death was largely reported in the media, starting discussions about bullying, the effect it has on youth, and gay bullying. ''[[The Huffington Post]]'',<ref name=Huff3>{{cite news|title=Joe Bell, Father Of Gay Teen Jadin, Discusses Cross-Country Anti-Bullying Walk|url=http://www.huffingtonpost.com/2013/05/03/joe-bell-cross-country-walk-_n_3209300.html|accessdate=15 March 2014|newspaper=The Huffington Post|date=3 May 2013}}</ref> ''[[Salon (website)|Salon]]'',<ref name=Toutonghi1>{{cite web|last=Toutonghi|first=Pauls|title="They ripped him apart": Searching for answers in the suicide of bullied teen Jadin Bell|url=http://www.salon.com/2013/09/08/%E2%80%9Cthey_ripped_him_apart%E2%80%9D_searching_for_answers_in_the_suicide_of_bullied_teen_jadin_bell/|publisher=Salon|accessdate=15 March 2014}}</ref> [[Oregon Public Broadcasting]],<ref name=opb1>{{cite web|title=La Grande Grapples With Bullying After Gay Teen's Death|url=http://www.opb.org/news/article/la-grande-grapples-with-bullying-after-gay-teens-death/|publisher=OPB|accessdate=15 March 2014}}</ref> [[Raw Story]],<ref name=Ferguson1>{{cite web|last=Ferguson|first=David|title=Bullied gay teen taken off life support after hanging self in schoolyard|url=http://www.rawstory.com/rs/2013/01/30/bullied-gay-teen-taken-off-life-support-after-hanging-self-in-schoolyard/|publisher=Raw Story|accessdate=15 March 2014}}</ref> [[GLAAD]],<ref name=GLAAD1>{{cite web|last=Hefferman|first=Dani|title=Jadin Bell|url=https://www.glaad.org/tags/jadin-bell|publisher=GLAAD|accessdate=15 March 2014}}</ref> ''[[PQ Monthly]]'',<ref name=Rook1>{{cite news|last=Rook|first=Erin|title=Project Believe in Me Founder Speaks Out on Bullying and Suicide|url=http://www.pqmonthly.com/project-believe-in-me-founder-speaks-out-on-bullying-and-suicide/11820|accessdate=15 March 2014|newspaper=PQ Monthly|date=29 January 2013}}</ref> ''[[PinkNews]]''<ref name=McCormick1>{{cite news|last=McCormick|first=Joseph Patrick|title=US: Gay teen taken off life support after hanging himself because of homophobic bullying|url=http://www.pinknews.co.uk/2013/01/30/us-gay-teen-taken-off-life-support-after-hanging-himself-because-of-homophobic-bullying/|accessdate=19 March 2014|newspaper=Pink News|date=30 January 2013}}</ref>  and many other media outlets reported on Bell's death. The media reported his suicide stemmed from being bullied for being gay, which Bell's father fully believed, stating "He was hurting so bad. Just the bullying at school. Yeah there were other issues, but ultimately it was all due to the bullying, for not being accepted for being gay."<ref name=KATU1>{{cite news|last=Tierney|first=John|title=Father killed on walk to honor bullied son who committed suicide|url=http://www.katu.com/news/local/Joe-Bell-killed-on-walk-to-honor-Jadin-Bell-227255411.html|accessdate=15 March 2014|newspaper=KATU|date=10 October 2013}}</ref>
* [[Suicide of Rehtaeh Parsons|Rehtaeh Parsons]] (1995–2013), age 17, a former [[Cole Harbour District High School]] student, attempted suicide by hanging<ref name="video tribute">"[http://www.huffingtonpost.ca/2013/04/09/rehtaeh-parsons-video_n_3046514.html Rehtaeh Parsons Video Tribute Marks Life Of 'Angel' (VIDEO)]," ''[[The Huffington Post]] Canada'', April 9, 2013, URL accessed April 14, 2013.</ref> on April 4, 2013, at her home in [[Dartmouth, Nova Scotia]], [[Canada]], leading to a [[coma]] and the decision to switch her [[life support]] machine off at [[Queen Elizabeth II Health Sciences Centre]] on April 7, 2013.<ref name="huffpost" /> Her death has been attributed to online distribution of photos of an alleged [[gang rape]] that occurred 17 months prior to her suicide, in November 2011.<ref name=huffpost>{{cite news|title=Rehtaeh Parsons, Canadian Girl, Dies After Suicide Attempt; Parents Allege She Was Raped By 4 Boys|url=http://www.huffingtonpost.com/2013/04/09/rehtaeh-parsons-girl-dies-suicide-rape-canada_n_3045033.html|work=The Huffington Post|accessdate=April 11, 2013|first=Andres|last=Jauregui|date=April 9, 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://edition.cnn.com/2013/04/10/justice/canada-teen-suicide/index.html?iref=allsearch |title=Canadian teen commits suicide after alleged rape, bullying |publisher=CNN |date= April 10, 2013|accessdate=April 11, 2013}}</ref> On a Facebook page set up in tribute to her daughter, Parsons' mother blamed the four boys who allegedly [[rape]]d and released images of her, the subsequent constant "bullying and messaging and harassment," and the failure of the [[Department of Justice (Canada)|Canadian justice system]], for her daughter's decision to commit suicide.<ref name="Slate-20130410">{{cite news|url=http://www.slate.com/articles/double_x/doublex/2013/04/rehtaeh_parsons_rape_case_why_do_these_keep_happening.single.html |title=Sexting Scourge |last=Bazelon |first=Emily |date=April 10, 2013 |work=Slate |accessdate=April 11, 2013}}</ref>
* [[Suicide of Rebecca Ann Sedwick|Rebecca Ann Sedwick]] (2000–2013), age 12, American middle school student who committed suicide by jumping due to bullying. Sedwick was a seventh grader at [[Crystal Lake Middle School (Lakeland, Florida)|Crystal Lake Middle School]] in [[Lakeland, Florida]]. Sedwick was cyberbullied and bullied in person for one and a half years. Two girls, ages 14 and 12, encouraged others to fight Sedwick, and sent her electronic messages encouraging her to kill herself.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.cbsnews.com/news/rebecca-sedwick-case-bullied-girl-and-her-tormentor-both-grew-up-in-disturbing-family-situations-says-sheriff/|title=Rebecca Sedwick Case: Bullied girl and her tormentor both grew up in "disturbing" family situations, says sheriff|access-date=2018-05-06|language=en}}</ref> In November 2012, her mother Tricia said that "she came home near tears every day".<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.cosmopolitan.com/lifestyle/advice/a6303/twelve-year-old-bully/|title=Who Are You Calling a Bully?|date=2014-04-08|work=Cosmopolitan|access-date=2018-05-06|language=en-US}}</ref> Rebecca committed suicide by jumping from a concrete silo tower to her death.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.orlandosentinel.com/news/breaking-news/os-rebecca-sedwick-suicide-lawsuit-20150408-story.html|title=Lawsuit: Polk investigation into Rebecca Sedwick's suicide was 'witch hunt, publicity stunt'|last=Stennett|first=Desiree|work=OrlandoSentinel.com|access-date=2018-05-06|language=en-US}}</ref> 
* [[August Ames]] (1994–2017) (born Mercedes Grabowski) was a [[Canada|Canadian]] [[pornographic]] actress and model. On December 5, 2017, Ames was found dead at her home in [[Camarillo, California]] at the age of 23.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://avn.com/business/articles/video/august-ames-passes-away-753019.html|title=August Ames Passes Away|author=Miller, Dan|work=[[AVN (magazine)|AVN]]|date=December 6, 2017|accessdate=December 7, 2017}}</ref> Her death was ruled a suicide by the Ventura County Medical Examiner's Office.<ref name="BNO">{{cite web|url=http://bnonews.com/news/index.php/news/id6821|title=Porn star August Ames found dead in suicide after online criticism|work=[[BNO News]]|date=December 6, 2017|accessdate=December 7, 2017}}</ref> Media outlets have insinuated Ames committed suicide following successive comments on Twitter in which she defended her refusal to perform in a pornographic movie with a man who had previously worked in gay pornography and sparking an "online firestorm".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.news.com.au/finance/work/at-work/porn-star-august-ames-dies-after-backlash-to-controversial-tweet/news-story/02f6071201d946c52c18372401a4239b|title=Porn star August Ames dies after backlash to controversial tweet|author=Chung, Frank|work=news.com.au|date=December 6, 2017|accessdate=December 7, 2017}}</ref> Ames wrote that the decision was out of concern for her health.  Some members of the gay community suggested her comments were homophobic and ill-informed about [[STI testing]] in the adult industry. Friends said she suffered from [[Depression (mood)|depression]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nydailynews.com/entertainment/porn-star-august-ames-dead-23-article-1.3681554|title=Porn Star August Ames Dies at 23|author=DeSantis, Rachel|work=[[New York Daily News]]|date=December 6, 2017|accessdate=December 7, 2017}}</ref> and Ames had previously discussed struggles with [[Bipolar disorder|bipolar]] and "[[Dissociative identity disorder|multiple personality]]" disorder.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.nydailynews.com/entertainment/porn-star-august-ames-revealed-depression-struggles-death-article-1.3683371|title=Porn star August Ames revealed depression struggles before death|work=NY Daily News|access-date=2017-12-11|language=en}}</ref>

